  "title": "Single replacement",
  "family": "single-replacement",
  "general_form": "A + BC -> B + AC",
  "summary": "A free element trades places with an element inside a compound: the newcomer combines, the displaced element goes free. One element is oxidized and the other reduced, so single replacement is always a redox reaction — its net-ionic view shows exactly which atoms swap electrons.",
  "regime": "rule-sourced",
  "source": "openstax-chemistry-2e",
  "conditions": [
    "One free element and one compound on each side (A + BC -> B + AC).",
    "Whether the swap actually happens depends on an activity ordering of the elements — a more reactive metal displaces a less reactive one. That ordering is its own sourced table."
  ],
  "misconceptions": [
    {
      "claim": "A single-replacement reaction is a plain double replacement.",
      "refute": "Look for a free element. A single replacement always has an uncombined element on each side; a double replacement has none — both partners stay combined and only swap."
    }
  ],
